{"title_page": "Robert Sommers", "text_new": "{{for|the American Civil War sailor|Robert Sommers (Medal of Honor)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image =\n| name = Robert Sommers\n| caption =\n| birth_date = January 3, 1911\n| birth_place = [[Leduc, Alberta]]\n| death_date= {{death date and age|2000|10|28|1911|1|3}}\n| death_place=[[Nanaimo, British Columbia]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|MLA]] for [[Rossland-Trail]]\n| term_start = 1952\n| term_end = 1958\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Douglas Turnbull]]\n| successor = [[Donald Leslie Brothers]]\n| party = [[British Columbia Social Credit Party|Social Credit]]  \n| occupation = Teacher, Politician, Piano tuner\n}}\n'''Robert Edward Sommers''' (January 3, 1911 &ndash; October 28, 2000) was an [[Alberta]]-born elementary school principal and a politician, who served as a [[British Columbia Social Credit Party|Social Credit]] Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] from 1952 to 1958, representing the riding of [[Rossland-Trail]] in the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[British Columbia]]. He served as Minister of Lands, Forests and Mines from until his resignation February 27, 1956.  He was tried and in 1958 was convicted of bribery and conspiracy making him the first [[cabinet minister]] in the [[British Commonwealth]] to serve a term of imprisonment for accepting bribes in connection with his office.\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in [[Leduc, Alberta]] in 1911,<ref name=\"normandin\"/> Sommers was the son of J. L. Sommers and Elsie Armonies, both natives of [[Germany]] who came to Canada in 1889.<ref name=\"normandin\"/>\n\nBefore entering politics, Sommers was an elementary school principal in [[Castlegar, British Columbia|Castlegar]], BC.  He was a trumpet player, a local band leader, a part-time insurance broker, a [[Kiwanis]] club president and a [[Volunteer fire department|volunteer firefighter]].<ref name=okeefe/>{{rp|7}}\n\nHe was married twice: first to Marion Henry in 1930 and then to Nona Samson in 1940.<ref name=\"normandin\">{{cite book |title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide, 1965 |last=Normandin |first=P G |year=1965}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was first elected as an MLA under the banner of the [[British Columbia Social Credit League]] as the member for Rossland-Trail in [[1952 British Columbia general election|1952]].<ref name = electionbc>{{Citation  | year = 1988  | publication-date = August 1988  | title = An Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986  | publisher = [[Elections BC]]  | url = http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf  | accessdate = 2009-08-20  | isbn = 0-7718-8677-2 }}</ref>{{rp|228}}  He was re-elected in [[1953 British Columbia general election|1953]], and [[1956 British Columbia general election|1956]].  In each election, against several opponents, his popular vote exceeded 50% of the votes cast including his last after he lost his cabinet position.<ref name = electionbc/>{{rp|228, 250, 269}}\n\nSommers resigned his seat automatically upon his conviction on November 7, 1958, for bribery and conspiracy.<ref name = electionbc/>{{rp|273}}\n\n==Scandal and trial==\nSommers downfall began when the Liberal opposition, particularly MLA [[Gordon Gibson, Sr.|Gordon Gibson]] accused Sommers of impropriety in the granting of a forest management licence to [[E. P. Taylor]]'s [[British Columbia Forest Products]] (BCFP).<ref name=baroud />\n\nThese licences were a new form of tenure in the forests of British Columbia introduced in 1948 based on the 1944 recommendations of the [[Gordon Sloan (politician)|Sloan]] Commission.  Large companies were given cutting rights over [[Crown land]] in perpetuity and in exchange were responsible for forest management, construction of access roads and [[fire fighting]].  The goal was to provide a sustained yield to supply mills over the long term by giving the licence holder a long-term interest in the productivity of the land.<ref name = okeefe/>{{rp|9}}  Forest management licences were extremely valuable.  There were accusations that companies made huge profits selling shares issued after a licence was granted before a single tree had been cut.<ref name = okeefe >{{Citation | last =O'Keefe | first =Betty | last2 =Macdonald | first2 =Ian | title =The Sommers Trial, The Felling of Trees and Tree Lords | place =Surrey, BC | publisher =Heritage House | year =1999 | isbn =1-895811-96-1 | url-access =registration | url =https://archive.org/details/sommersscandalfe0000okee }}</ref>{{rp|49}}<ref name=baroud /> E. P. Taylor's [[Argus Corporation]], which incorporated British Columbia Forest Products to run its BC forest operations in 1946, had been turned down for a forest management licence in 1948.  After he became the cabinet minister in charge of granting forest management licences, Sommers, who was then in awkward financial circumstances personally, had meetings with Taylor and the management of Argus at which BCFP sought a licence.  Taylor, BC premier [[W. A. C. Bennett]] and Sommers met at the [[The Empress (hotel)|Empress Hotel]] in January 1955.  Afterwards, Bennett directed Sommers to make the deal. The result was that BCFP was granted FML #22 which covered {{convert|250000|acre|km2}} between [[Port Renfrew, British Columbia|Port Renfrew]] and [[Estevan Point]] along the west coast of [[Vancouver Island]].<ref name=okeefe/>{{rp|43}}\n\nA commission led by Justice Arthur Lord found no basis for the charges and Sommers responded to the accusations by suing Vancouver lawyer David Sturdy for libel.  The Bennett government stonewalled in the legislature on the basis that the matter was before the courts until Sommers was dropped from cabinet in 1956.  In November 1957 he was arrested and charged with bribery.  The next year, he and Wick Gray were convicted.  BCFP was acquitted. Sommers was sentenced to 5 years in prison but was released after 28 months.  While imprisoned, he learned the piano tuning trade.  He established a piano business on Vancouver Island after his release in 1961.<ref name=enbc>{{citation |last= Francis (ed) |first= Daniel |editor=Francis, Daniel |title=Encyclopedia of British Columbia |url= http://www.knowbc.com/ |origyear=1999 |year=2000 |publisher = Harbour Publishing |isbn = 1-55017-200-X |page= 667 }}</ref> Sommers was convicted on five of seven charges of receiving bribes.  He was found to have received $607 worth of rugs, $3,000 in bonds, $1,000 in cash and $2,500 sent by telegraph making him the first person in the Commonwealth found guilty of conspiring to accept bribes while serving as a Minister.<ref name=baroud>{{citation |last=Baroud |first=Aline |last2=Gibbs |first2=Andrew |title=Improper use of public office |publisher=Department of Justice, Canada |url=http://www.justice.gc.ca/eng/pi/icg-gci/po-cp/page03.html |accessdate=2009-08-29 |edition=Bribery}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nDuring his time in prison, Sommers learned the trade of [[piano tuning]] and restoration from a fellow inmate.  He took up residence on Vancouver Island after his release and established a business in that field.<ref name=okeefe/>{{rp|169}}  Sommers died at the age of 89 at a hospital in [[Nanaimo]], [[British Columbia]] on October 28, 2000.<ref>Lone B.C. minister to be jailed dies at 89: Robert Sommers, who gained notoriety for taking bribes and paying a price, wound up as a piano tuner: [Final Edition]\nWatts, Richard. Times - Colonist; Victoria, B.C. [Victoria, B.C]30 Oct 2000: A1 / FRONT.</ref><ref>{{Citation  | publisher=CBCNews.ca  | title = Socred cabinet minister jailed for corruption, dies at 89  | date=October 30, 2000  | accessdate=2009-08-20  | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2000/10/30/bc_sommersobit001030.html }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Sommers and Gray v. The Queen. - [http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/1959/1959rcs0-678/1959rcs0-678.html Decision of the Supreme Court of Canada, 25 June 1959] - [1959] [[Supreme Court Reports (Canada)|Supreme Court Reports]], pages 678\u2013690.\n* Paddy Sherman, Bennett, Toronto, [[McClelland and Stewart]], 1966\n*[https://archive.org/details/vancouverltd0000guts/page/82 <!-- quote=Robert Sommers BC. --> Internet Archive] Donald Gutstein, Vancouver Ltd. mentions the Sommers defence in an article about Vancouver lawyer Jack Nicholson\n*The Baroud Gibbs paper of The International Cooperation Group is also available at the [http://www.aps-pub.com/proceedings/1471/110.pdf Department of Justice] website.\n*The Sommers scandal was the subject of [http://www.westerncanadatheatre.bc.ca/davidrossmem.htm a play by David Ross]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Alexander Douglas Turnbull]]|\n title=[[Rossland-Trail|MLA for Rossland-Trail]]|\n after=[[Donald Leslie Brothers]]|\n years=1952&ndash;1958\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n before=&nbsp;|\n title=[[Minister of Lands, Forests and Mines]]|\n after=[[Ray Gillis Williston]]|\n years=1952&ndash;1956\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sommers, Robert Edward}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Columbia Social Credit Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:People from Leduc, Alberta]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Corruption in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians convicted of crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American Civil War sailor|Robert Sommers (Medal of Honor)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image =\n| name = Robert Sommers\n| caption =\n| birth_date = January 3, 1911\n| birth_place = [[Leduc, Alberta]]\n| death_date= {{death date and age|2000|10|28|1911|1|3}}\n| death_place=[[Nanaimo, British Columbia]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|MLA]] for [[Rossland-Trail]]\n| term_start = 1952\n| term_end = 1958\n| predecessor = [[Alexander Douglas Turnbull]]\n| successor = [[Donald Leslie Brothers]]\n| party = [[British Columbia Social Cre